Nehawu has already said that President Jacob Zuma should step down while others back Cyril Ramaphosa to be the next ANC leader. JOHANNESBURG - The African National Congress (ANC) says it condemns unions belonging to the Congress of South African Trade Unions (Cosatu) for making pronouncements about the party s leadership elections.The National Education, Health and Allied Workers Union (Nehawu) has already said that President Jacob Zuma should step down while the Communication Workers Union (CWU) says it s discussing whether it will also say Zuma should resign.Other unions have said that they want to back Deputy President Cyril Ramaphosa to be the next leader of the ANC.ANC spokesperson Zizi Kodwa says Cosatu unions that have spoken about who could lead the ANC are breaking alliance protocol. We think Cosatu affiliates must respect the internal processes of the ANC. At the moment, the leadership of the ANC is meeting with branches to discuss some set of principles to determine the kind of leader and leadership which must lead us. He says Cosatu members should actually be helping to foster unity among ANC structures.This statement comes as Cosatu s central executive committee is due to meet next week and is expected to discuss President Zuma.Meanwhile, the Communication Workers Union (CWU) says that after a series of engagements with its members, there was a strong sentiment that Zuma must step down.General Secretary Aubrey Tshabalala says the president has put the country in crisis. Following our struggles in the Post Office, Telkom and others there was a strong sentiment that the president of the country and the president of the ANC must step aside. (Edited by Masechaba Sefularo)